I am in one of the hardest times I have known. So far the hardest have been my mom’s death, my divorce and some gross sexual harassment. I got a little break this past weekend and went to the Oregon coast. It is one of the most beautiful and rejuvenating places I’ve ever been. #pacificnorthwest #pnwonderland #nofilter

When going through tough times it’s so helpful to get lots of sleep, drink lots of water and eat well. I made roasted chicken and sausage with peppery vinegar and white wine. (Drank a bunch of wine, too. 😉)
Apples from my tree, made into a pie. Mantra: when times are tough, eat extra well.
I am pretty excited to have been asked to participate on this taskforce led by @govtinakotek
#silveradosilverstein aka Silly
My world continues to be tough,  it’s a lot to hold on to. I’m taking a little break and getting a different view. This is one of my favorite views.

I was asked by the @americanredcross to post this, it is not a paid or sponsored post. Over Covid I realized there was a national blood shortage and made a commitment to give blood and platelets as often as I am able. Are you able to help? There are people who aren’t getting proper medical care because there is not enough blood donated. If you can help, it could make a huge difference for someone.

Ringing in the new year with hope for an easier year ahead. My wonderful farmer @stewardsvalleyfarm gave me grapes, so I made them into this cocktail w St Germain, honey, @amalgadistillery gin and Lillet blanc. Shannah Tovah. 🍯
So, what’s your advice for getting through long periods of stress in your life? Help me out here, I know you guys have a good advice. What helps you when you have no choice but to go through it?
I cooked @sfwcfiesta today, here’s my dish! Seared albacore w ras el hanout, hatch chilies and yogurt sauce.
New Mexico is a looker ❤️

The Common Good Project is completely out of funding. I am looking for assistance so that I can provide propane throughout the winter for heat and cooking, batteries, and other winter time necessities. If you are able to contribute, it would be greatly appreciated. 

You can send it to my Venmo (@jenn-louis) or through the Trash For Peace website (trashforpeace.org). They are our fiscal sponsors. They take 10% of donations for fiscal management. Funding sent to my Venmo goes directly to those I care for.
Last Thursday I had the pleasure of joining my friend Meg on her dog bus for the afternoon. It was pretty awesome! 🐶 ❤️

I met Hanan on an airplane coming home from Israel. She introduced herself as a Christian Palestinian, the peaceful kind. In turn, I introduced myself as a Jewish American, the peaceful kind. We chatted about all sorts of things. She now lives in San Jose and still love to cook the food she grew up with. Not knowing my interest in chicken soup, she shared her mother’s recipe. Her advice is that the soup should only have a small handful of rice, because the broth is most important, especially when someone is sick.

The story goes like this: my mom‘s matzoh balls were never tender as she wished until she made a batch of matzoh balls, turned off the heat and left them in the poaching liquid while we went to services at the synagogue. When we returned to eat dinner, the balls, sitting in the warm water for an hour or two, softened and pumped up. Her, and now my, cooking method was changed forever. I find it a perfect balance balance is poaching for 30 minutes, then letting the matzoh balls, rest of the poaching liquid, covered, for a further 30 minutes. The centers of the balls become a little chewy and exteriors are soft and fluffy. Just the way I like them.
#wewillnotforget #neveragain

My non-Jewish friend doesn’t pretend to understand what I’m going through. Instead, she knitted for me a really soft heart bean bag that I could hold for comfort. ❤️
When your non-Jewish friends know exactly what to say.

These Shabbat candlesticks are the only thing that my family brought when they came to the US from Eastern Europe three generations ago. I grew up with them on every Shabbat table, and every holiday table. Last night I lit them at my house for the first time. 🕯️ 🕯️❤️

I haven’t had much good stuff in my life for a while. It’s been a hard, long stretch. Staggering family illnesses, general life bullshit and a really horrific war. 

But, today I had a really cool breakthrough. This is Leprechaun. I’ve been working with him on and off for about three years on the street. Today he called me by name and thanked me for all I’ve given to him. I felt like I was going to melt into a puddle! My heart was so warm and full.
Let’s make latkes every day during Hanukkah. Here are two recipes that I published years ago, just go to @vice (vice.com) and search for the recipes.
Shabbat shalom. 🕯️🕯️

I was a member of the task force. I have been on the streets working with people who are homeless for over three years. No one ever asked me for my opinion. I’m not quite sure what the point was.

Sfinge, 
Moroccan doughnuts for Hanukkah! 🕎

One of my favorite Jewish traditions is lighting a 24 hour candle on the anniversary of a loved one’s death. It’s nice to bring some light in and think of special memories. I tend to see the candle at different times during the 24 hour period and  keep constant thought on that person. ❤️
A message from a friend. He gets me. ❤️

It doesn’t feel much like the wonder of a new year to me. My sister is in hospice, my dad is struggling, my partner’s sister is not well. The war makes me deeply sad, every day. I’m dealing with antisemitism in my neighborhood. My tenants decided it was cool to grow about 300 weed plants in my rental home and cause serious damage, and they aren’t taking responsibility. (They didn’t even share the harvest with me. 😉)
 
So, it just feels like another day, another week, another year. It’s hard to look ahead to anything more than sad. 

This is a photo of my sister, when she was young enough that nothing significantly bad had happened to her. She is holding my childhood dog, Daiquiri, as a puppy.

I went to a show in December, when I left the theater I looked up and saw crows roosting in this tree. Maybe it was a sign, who knows. It was pretty magical.

I’ve been laying in bed with my sister and caring for her while she is in hospice. It’s an honor to care for those in need, and terribly sad and grueling at the same time. My heart is broken, and I am so glad that I can spend these last days with her.
